# /git-commit — Structured Commit

## Purpose
Create commits following Conventional Commits with clear, descriptive messages.

## Pre-validation
1. Check for staged changes (`git diff --cached --stat`)
2. If no staged changes, warn the user — staging is their responsibility
3. NEVER run `git add .` automatically

## Process
1. Analyze staged changes (`git diff --cached`)
2. Classify the change type:
   - `feat`: new feature
   - `fix`: bug fix
   - `refactor`: refactoring without behavior change
   - `docs`: documentation
   - `test`: tests
   - `chore`: maintenance, configs
   - `style`: formatting, lint
   - `perf`: performance
   - `ci`: CI/CD
   - `build`: build, dependencies
3. Identify the scope (module or affected area)
4. Generate concise message (max 72 chars in title)

## Format
```
type(scope): short description

Optional body with more details about the change.
Why it was made, relevant context.

Co-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
```

## Rules
- Title always in lowercase
- No period at end of title
- Body separated from title by blank line
- Always include `Co-Authored-By` when Claude participated
- If multiple modules were changed, use generic scope or list them
- Breaking changes: add `!` after type — `feat!: breaking change`
